<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<?import javafx.scene.control.Button?>
<?import javafx.scene.control.Label?>
<?import javafx.scene.control.TextArea?>
<?import javafx.scene.layout.AnchorPane?>
<?import javafx.scene.layout.VBox?>

<AnchorPane xmlns="http://javafx.com/javafx/23.0.1" xmlns:fx="http://javafx.com/fxml/1" fx:controller="org.example.motionsim.Controller.UserManualController">
    <children>
            <VBox alignment="TOP_CENTER" spacing="10" AnchorPane.leftAnchor="10" AnchorPane.rightAnchor="10" AnchorPane.topAnchor="20">
                    <Label style="-fx-font-size: 18px; -fx-font-weight: bold;" text="User Guide" />
            <Label style="-fx-font-size: 14px; -fx-font-weight: bold;" text="Game Explanation:" />
            <TextArea fx:id="gameExplanation" editable="false" prefHeight="150" wrapText="true">
                <text>
        -The game uses the study of physics,waves and mechanics to fire a ball with a spring.
        -You, my favourite player, are able to change the angle of the spring, the spring constant(k), the gravity(g), and you will be finally able to change the spring
        by dragging the spring back and letting go!
        -The velocity(v) that the ball is thrown with depends on how far back the spring has been pulled.
                </text>
            </TextArea>
                <Label style="-fx-font-size: 16px;-fx-font-weight: bold;" text="The Science Behind the Game " />
            <Label style="-fx-font-size: 14px;-fx-font-weight:bold;" text="Science Explanation:" />
                <TextArea fx:id="scienceExplanation" editable="false" prefHeight="100" wrapText="true">
            <text>
                -The force exerted by the spring follows the Hooke's Law: F = -kx
                -The launch velocity(v) depends on the energy stored in the compressed spring:
                -U = 1/2kx²
            </text>
            </TextArea>
                <Label style="-fx-font-size: 20; -fx-font-weight: bold;" text="How To Play The Game" />
                <TextArea editable="false" text="Objective: &#10;The game simulates spring physics and projectile motion, where the goal is to adjust the spring and launch a projectile.                 &#10;Step 1:Adjust the String             &#10;-Use the spring slider in Game Menu to change stiffness. &#10;-Higher stiffness means a bigger and stronger launch. &#10;Step 2: Adjust Gravity             &#10;-Use the gravity slider to change how fast objects fall.                 &#10;Step 3: Set Difficulty             &#10;-Easy: Slower gravity &#10;-Normal: Standard settings and normal gravity &#10;-Hard: Faster gravity, requires precision. &#10;Step 4: Launch The Projectile&#10;-Drag the spring back and release it at launch. &#10;Step 5: Control Center Settings &#10;-Timer: You as the user, can turn the simulation timer ON and OFF             &#10;-Sound Effects: You as the user, can enable or disable the simulation's sound effects             &#10;-Music Volume: You as the user, can adjust the volume of the simultaion's music                 &#10;Step 6: Save, Exit, or Reset &#10;-Save: Store Settings             &#10;-Exit: Close settings menu and go back to the game            &#10;-Reset: Revert to default values              &#10;Physics Behind The Game:            &#10; Hooke's Law: F = -kx             &#10;Energy In Spring: U = 1/2 kx²            &#10; Kinetic Energy: K = 1/2mv²             &#10;Gravitational Potential Energy: U = mgh             &#10;Gravitational Potential Energy(Orbital Motion): U = GMm/r             &#10;Escape Velocity = √(2GM/R)             &#10;Total Energy(Projectile Motion): E = 1/2mv² + mgh" wrapText="true" />
            </VBox>
        <Button fx:id="closeButton" onAction="#closeUserManual" text="Back" />
    </children>
</AnchorPane>
